                                <title2
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1651545824678,1651545825668]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2023-11-02T12:21:16.421-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    jcr:title="Q: How has living in other countries with different cultures impacted you and your children? "
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/title/v2/title"
                                    type="h5"
                                    variant="h"/>
                                <text2
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1659545835858]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2023-10-06T11:09:28.134-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>&lt;b>Sofie&lt;/b>: Growing up in Sweden, I rarely saw families with one parent who stayed at home, additionally everyone contributed to the household in some way regardless of status or profession, whether it was working, cooking, laundry, etc. Because of our upbringing, Mattias and I were adamant about teaching our sons how to take care of themselves and the spaces they live in. It really shows in their love of cooking and offers to help around the home (and even with our neighbors). I’ve had other parents tell me how impressed they are when my boys visit their friends and help in the kitchen!&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
                            </container4_copy_1970_26452752>
                            <quote_copy
                                cq:styleIds="[1000000000040,1000000000000]"
                                jcr:created="{Date}2023-10-06T11:07:31.965-04:00"
                                jcr:createdBy="chiucx"
                                jcr:lastModified="{Date}2023-10-06T13:41:55.513-04:00"
                                jcr:lastModifiedBy="chiucx"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/quote"
                                attributionName="Sofie Berg"
                                attributionTitle="Therapeutic Area Head, Global Medical Affairs"
                                bgImageModifiers="resMode=sharp2&amp;op_sharpen=1"
                                fileReference="/content/dam/abbvie-com2/images/stories/working-parent-2023/sofie-berg-quote.jpg"
                                imageModifiers="resMode=sharp2&amp;op_sharpen=1"
                                quote="By being myself with my colleagues, they’re able to see me as not only a co-worker but a strong, single parent.”"
                                quoteType="regular"
                                textSize="h0"/>
                            <container4_copy_1970_1670981382
                                cq:styleIds="[1653545847150,1653242825678,1653545825687,1653545835982]"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/container/v2/container">
                                <title2
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1651545824678,1651545825668]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2023-11-02T12:21:25.195-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    jcr:title="Q: Do you have any words of guidance or support that you’d like to share with other working parents at AbbVie? "
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/title/v2/title"
                                    type="h5"
                                    variant="h"/>
                                <text2
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1659545835858]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2023-10-06T11:10:52.187-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>&lt;b>Lisa: &lt;/b>One piece of advice I received is to remember that “wherever you are, be all there”. When you’re at work, focus on the task at hand, but when you’re at home, it’s okay to turn off that part of your brain and be in the moment with your family. Your kids might not remember all the good times or the bad times, but they’ll remember when you were present with them.&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>&lt;b>Sofie: &lt;/b>Be authentic because you never know who you might help with your story and how they might be able to help you too. Using myself as an example, I haven’t spoken much about my struggle, and it’s been an incredibly tough year. But by being myself with my colleagues, they’re able to see me as not only a co-worker but a strong, single parent. If the doctor or school calls about my sons, there isn’t anybody else to answer and because I’ve shared that part of my life authentically, my team has been so caring and empathetic. I’m very grateful for the support I received from AbbVie when my life suddenly was turned upside down and I want to thank my manager and team for supporting me and my needs for occasional flexibility.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
